COMP30760 Assignment 1 Sample 2 - Task 2 + 3¶

In this assignment we data data from the Global Warming API. The API offers current data, graphs, and details on the Earth's present temperature and the levels of greenhouse gases in the atmosphere.

This notebook covers Task 2 and 3. We will use all of the JSON data collected during Task 1 to perform the analysis process.

As a preprocessing step, we need to convert the decimal-based dates to a more useful format:

In [5]:
def convert_time(t):
    parts = t.split('.')
    # first part is the year
    year = int(parts[0])
    # do we also have a month component?
    if len(parts) == 1:
        return datetime(year, 1, 1)
    # convert to a proper month
    month = math.ceil(float('0.' + parts[1]) * 365 / 30)
    return datetime(year, month, 1)

# apply to all values
df_temperature["date"] = df_temperature["time"].apply(lambda x: convert_time(x))
# drop the old column
df_temperature.drop("time", inplace=True, axis=1)
# set the new column as the index and sort it
df_temperature = df_temperature.set_index(["date"]).sort_index()
# check the DataFrame

In [6]:
dfg = {}
for gas in gases:
    print("Processing %s" % gas)
    # extract the part of the JSON data that we need
    data_field = gas.split("-")[0]
    # turn it into a DataFrame
    dfg[gas] = pd.DataFrame(raw_data[gas][data_field])
    # CO2 dates are slightly different
    if gas == "co2":
        dfg[gas]["date"] = pd.to_datetime(
            dict(year=dfg[gas]["year"], month=dfg[gas]["month"], day=dfg[gas]["day"]))
        dfg[gas].drop("year", inplace=True, axis=1)
        dfg[gas].drop("month", inplace=True, axis=1)
        dfg[gas].drop("day", inplace=True, axis=1)
    # otherwise, use the function we defined earlier
    else:
        dfg[gas]["date"] = dfg[gas]["date"].apply(lambda x: convert_time(x))
    # change the index now and sort it   
    dfg[gas] = dfg[gas].set_index(["date"]).sort_index()
    print("DataFrame has %d rows, %d columns" % dfg[gas].shape)
    print("Columns:", dfg[gas].columns)
    # we need to convert all of the columns to floats
    for col in dfg[gas].columns:
        dfg[gas][col] = dfg[gas][col].astype(float)
    # check the column types now
    print("Types", dfg[gas].dtypes)
    # check a sample
    display(dfg[gas].head(5))
    print()

# define a simple function to format date ranges for the index in the specified DataFrame
def format_range(df):
    dmin, dmax = df.index.min(), df.index.max()
    return "%s to %s" % (dmin.strftime("%Y-%m-%d"), dmax.strftime("%Y-%m-%d"))

# check the range for the temperature variable
print('{v: <16} {r}'.format(v="temperature", r=format_range(df_temperature)))
# check the range for the data for the different gases
for gas in gases:
    print('{v: <16} {r}'.format(v=gas, r=format_range(dfg[gas])))

# convenience function for time series plots
def create_ts_plot(data, title, ylabel, color="navy"):
    # create a time series plot
    ax = data.plot(figsize=(9, 4.3), legend=False, lw=2, zorder=3, color=color)
    plt.title(title, fontsize=fontsize-1)
    plt.ylabel(ylabel)
    plt.xlabel(None)
    ax.xaxis.grid(False)
    ax.yaxis.grid(True)
    return ax



     



















In [12]:

               "Temperature Change", "darkred");

Conclusion¶






















In this assignment we looked at the relationship between various greenhouse gases and land temperature changes. We see a strong correlation between these measures, with temperatures particularly trending upwards since the 1970s. However, one limitation is that we only have recent reliable data for gases such as CO2 and NO2. Further historic data might allow us to quanitfy the trends more reliably.


Further work could look at integrating ocean temperature change data from the API, while also looking at how temperature change is impact on polar ice cover. We could also conduct further analysis of the temperature change outliers and whether these events are become increasingly frequent in recent years.
